  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a lived reality for many who've seen their potential dimmed by the very idea that they don't belong. Growing up in a small coastal town in southern Italy, I witnessed firsthand how assumptions about who belongs in science and technology can create barriers. My parents, one with a PhD and the other with a vocational diploma, taught me the value of curiosity and hard work, but even they couldn't shield me from the subtle whispers that came with being an immigrant child in a system that often assumes certain paths are for some but not others. In my early years, I recall feeling a quiet anxiety when I'd see classmates from my school in Lecce who seemed to know more about physics than I did—this wasn't just about knowledge but about belonging. Stereotype threat is the psychological burden that comes from being perceived as part of a group that's been stereotyped as less capable. It's not just about the fear of failure but about the fear of being labeled or misunderstood. I've seen this in my own life, especially when I volunteered at local science workshops for children. Some kids would hesitate to ask questions, not because they didn't understand, but because they thought they might be 'not smart enough' to get the answers right. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it demands a shift in how we create learning environments. We need to foster inclusivity by celebrating diverse backgrounds and encouraging all students to explore STEM without fear of judgment. It's about creating spaces where everyone feels they can contribute, where the focus is on growth, not on labels. This isn't just about fixing a problem but about building a future where everyone has the opportunity to thrive in science and technology. As someone who's spent time in both academic and community settings, I believe that when we actively work to dismantle these stereotypes, we're not only helping individuals but strengthening the very fabric of our communities.",
